import os

# Path to the training data folder
train_folder_path = "C:/Users/smart/Documents/All Courses Assignments files first trial/Foundations of Machine Learning/train"

# Getting a list of class folders
class_folders = [folder for folder in os.listdir(train_folder_path) if os.path.isdir(os.path.join(train_folder_path, folder))]

# Creating a dictionary to store class names and their corresponding image counts
class_image_counts = {}

# Iterating through each class folder and count the number of images
for class_folder in class_folders:
    class_path = os.path.join(train_folder_path, class_folder)
    num_images = len(os.listdir(class_path))
    class_image_counts[class_folder] = num_images

# Sorting the classes based on image counts in descending order
sorted_classes = sorted(class_image_counts.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

# Getting the top three classes
top_three_classes = sorted_classes[:3]

# Printing the top three classes and their image counts
print("Top Three Classes:")
for class_name, num_images in top_three_classes:
    print(f"{class_name}: {num_images} images")

# Creating a list of top three class folders
top_three_class_folders = [os.path.join(train_folder_path, class_name) for class_name, _ in top_three_classes]

import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.image import ImageDataGenerator

# Setting my folder paths
base_folder_path = "C:/Users/smart/Documents/All Courses Assignments files first trial/Foundations of Machine Learning"
train_folder_name = "train"
img_size = (224, 224)
batch_size = 12  

# Specifying the classes based on the top three classes I identified earlier
selected_classes = ["RUFOUS TREPE", "HOUSE FINCH", "D-ARNAUDS BARBET"]

# Setting up data augmentation for the training dataset
train_data_gen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255,
    rotation_range=20,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    brightness_range=[0.5, 1.5],
    shear_range=0.1,
    zoom_range=0.3,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)

# Creating a generator for the original training dataset using flow_from_directory method
train_generator = train_data_gen.flow_from_directory(
    os.path.join(base_folder_path, train_folder_name),
    target_size=img_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    classes=selected_classes
)

# Retrieving a batch of augmented images along with their labels
augmented_images, _ = next(train_generator)

# Displaying the augmented images in a 3x4 grid using matplotlib
fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 4, figsize=(12, 12))
axes = axes.flatten()

for img, ax in zip(augmented_images, axes):
    ax.imshow(img)
    ax.axis('off')

plt.show()

from tensorflow.keras.applications import VGG16
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, Flatten, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ModelCheckpoint

# Setting our folder paths
base_folder_path = "C:/Users/smart/Documents/All Courses Assignments files first trial/Foundations of Machine Learning"
train_folder_name = "train"
validation_folder_name = "valid"
img_size = (224, 224)
batch_size = 32

# Specifying the classes based on the top three classes I identified earlier
selected_classes = ["RUFOUS TREPE", "HOUSE FINCH", "D-ARNAUDS BARBET"]

# Setting up data augmentation for the training dataset
train_data_gen = ImageDataGenerator(
    rescale=1./255,
    rotation_range=30,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    brightness_range=[0.5, 1.5],
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.3,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    fill_mode='nearest'
)

# Setting up data normalization for the validation dataset
validation_data_gen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255)

# Creating generators for the training and validation datasets
train_generator = train_data_gen.flow_from_directory(
    os.path.join(base_folder_path, train_folder_name),
    target_size=img_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    classes=selected_classes
)

validation_generator = validation_data_gen.flow_from_directory(
    os.path.join(base_folder_path, validation_folder_name),
    target_size=img_size,
    batch_size=batch_size,
    class_mode='categorical',
    classes=selected_classes
)

# Loading the pre-trained VGG16 model
base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(224, 224, 3))

# Creating a new model for fine-tuning with regularization and dropout
model = Sequential()
model.add(base_model)
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
model.add(Dropout(0.5))
model.add(Dense(len(selected_classes), activation='softmax'))

# Freezing the layers of the pre-trained model
for layer in base_model.layers:
    layer.trainable = False

# Compiling the model
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.0001), loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Implementing early stopping and model checkpoint callbacks
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3, restore_best_weights=True)
model_checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint('best_model.h5', monitor='val_loss', save_best_only=True)

# Training the model on the original and augmented datasets
history_original = model.fit(
    train_generator,
    epochs=15,
    validation_data=validation_generator,
    callbacks=[early_stopping, model_checkpoint]
)

# Loading the best model from the training phase
model.load_weights('best_model.h5')

# Unfreezing some layers for fine-tuning
for layer in model.layers[0].layers[-6:]:
    layer.trainable = True

# Recompiling the model after unfreezing
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.00001), loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

# Training the model on the augmented dataset
history_augmented = model.fit(
    train_generator,
    epochs=15,
    validation_data=validation_generator,
    callbacks=[early_stopping]
)

# Evaluating the model on the validation set
evaluation = model.evaluate(validation_generator)
print(f"Validation Loss: {evaluation[0]}, Validation Accuracy: {evaluation[1]}")

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, classification_report, precision_recall_curve, auc
from tensorflow.keras.utils import to_categorical

# ...

# One-hot encode true labels
true_labels_one_hot = to_categorical(true_labels, num_classes=len(class_names))

# Converting probabilities to binary predictions
pred_labels = np.round(pred_probs)

# Confusion Matrix
conf_mat = confusion_matrix(true_labels, pred_labels)
print("Confusion Matrix:")
print(conf_mat)

# Classification Report
class_names = validation_generator.class_indices.keys()
print("Classification Report:")
print(classification_report(true_labels, pred_labels, target_names=class_names, zero_division=1))

# Precision-Recall Curve
precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(true_labels_one_hot.ravel()[:len(pred_probs)], pred_probs)
pr_auc = auc(recall, precision)

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
plt.plot(recall, precision, label=f'PR AUC = {pr_auc:.2f}')
plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
plt.title('Precision-Recall Curve')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Making predictions on the validation set
predictions = model.predict(validation_generator)

# Getting the class indices for each prediction
predicted_classes = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)

# Getting the true class indices
true_classes = validation_generator.classes

# Finding the indices where predictions do not match true labels
misclassified_indices = np.where(predicted_classes != true_classes)[0]

# Displaying a few misclassified images
num_misclassified = min(5, len(misclassified_indices))
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 8))
for i in range(num_misclassified):
    index = misclassified_indices[i]
    image_path = validation_generator.filepaths[index]
    true_label = selected_classes[true_classes[index]]
    predicted_label = selected_classes[predicted_classes[index]]

    # Loading and display the misclassified image
    img = plt.imread(image_path)
    plt.subplot(1, num_misclassified, i + 1)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.title(f'True: {true_label}\nPredicted: {predicted_label}')
    plt.axis('off')

plt.show()
